                <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">1. Eliminating the "Dual-Input Paradox" in Delivery & Ride-Hailing</h2>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 text-sm mt-4">
                    <div class="bg-red-50/50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-100">
                        <strong class="text-red-800 font-semibold block mb-1">The Friction (Traditional Way):</strong>
                        Users select their precise house pin on a map, but the interface forces them to pick their province/district from dropdown lists. Due to human error, a user might drop a pin in <code class="bg-white px-1 rounded">Chilanzar</code> but select <code class="bg-white px-1 rounded">Yunusabad</code> from the list. This creates conflicting database properties, causing taxi dispatches or food orders to route to completely wrong branches.
                    </div>
                    <div class="bg-green-50/50 p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-100">
                        <strong class="text-green-800 font-semibold block mb-1">The Kettu Solution (Automatic UX):</strong>
                        Dropdown menus are completely purged from the address selection flow. The client performs exactly one seamless action—dropping a map pin. Your server passes those background coordinates to Kettu. Within milliseconds, Kettu returns the immutable natural key (<code class="bg-white px-1 rounded font-mono text-xs">"chilanzar"</code>), auto-assigning the transaction to the perfect local branch with zero human mistakes.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

